<DOC><DOCNO> AP890327-0163 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-27-89 2048EST</FILEID><FIRST>u i AM-Haiti-Clash 2ndLd-Writethru   03-27 0371</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Haiti-Clash, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0672,0380</SECOND><HEAD>Machete-Wielding Mob Attacks U.S. Missionaries</HEAD><HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with witnesses' comments on detailsof accident and attack. No pickup</HEAD><TEXT>   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti (AP) _ A mob with machetes attacked andseriously wounded seven U.S. missionaries after a pickup truckcarrying the Americans accidentally ran over two Haitians, RadioHaiti-Inter reported Monday.   In Washington, a State Department official put the number ofAmericans injured in the incident Sunday at 12, but said none washurt seriously. The official, speaking on condition of anonymity,said some Americans were hospitalized and that others were treatedand released.   The report by independent Radio Haiti-Inter said seven FreeMethodist Church missionaries were hospitalized in seriouscondition with multiple machete wounds after the attack, and thetwo Haitians suffered broken legs.   The missionaries and Haitians were not immediately identified.The State Department said it was not authorized to release themissionaries' names because of the Privacy Act.   The radio station said the attack occurred after the pickuptruck went out of control and plowed into the Haitians, who werecelebrating the Lenten season on a highway near Leogane, about 18miles southwest of Port-au-Prince.   Bystanders stoned the truck and set upon the missionaries withmachetes, the report said. It did not say what caused the truckdriver to lose control.   Two witnesses told The Associated Press the missionaries weresaved by the arrival of a soldier, who fired a shot into the air toquiet the crowd.   The man and woman, who spoke on condition of anonymity, saidsome of the missionaries also were armed and that they fired theirweapons.   The witnesses said they were driving home to Port-au-Prince fromLeogane region when they came upon the scene. They described it as``nightmarish.''   The truck struck the crowd, and the pedestrians interpreted thataction as a deliberate attempt to harm them, the witnesses said.   Bands of revelers known as ``ra-ras'' are a Lenten seasontradition in Haiti. They wander about, chanting and playing drumsand bamboo trumpets.   The State Department official said the Americans planned toreturn to the United States on Tuesday. The official did not knowwhether the trip was scheduled as a result of the Sunday incident.</TEXT></DOC>